  "prompt": "Is using \"hairs\" instead of \"hair\" grammatically incorrect?",
  "response": "The use of \"hairs\" instead of \"hair\" is not necessarily grammatically incorrect, but it depends on the context. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. **\"Hair\" (singular)**:  \n   - Refers to the collective mass of hair on someone's head or body.  \n   - Example: \"She has beautiful hair.\"  \n\n2. **\"Hairs\" (plural)**:  \n   - Refers to individual strands of hair.  \n   - Example: \"I found a few gray hairs on my pillow.\"  \n\nSo, if you're talking about individual strands, \"hairs\" is correct. If you're referring to hair as a whole, use \"hair.\"  \nIncorrect usage would be something like \"I washed my hairs\" when you mean all the hair on your head\u2014instead, \"I washed my hair\" would be appropriate.",
